    {
      "id": "OJBeoq8HyO0nC6P3cDsyc",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 3313.5661927315673,
      "y": -1793.6467936345068,
      "width": 2706.886474609375,
      "height": 597.5982087739552,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a7",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 547902529,
      "version": 2269,
      "versionNonce": 514472960,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783935649889,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "- Reliablity: we should be able to start our workflow from where it failed.\n\n- Scalablity: as we have assume 100k workflows from 1M runs atleast once. then we can say on avg atleast 10 workflow runs per day and nearly at any seconds nearly 10 are running. \n\n        -> 10 w/f running per day from 1M. \n        -> at any given second atleast 10 w/f are running. QPS for new workflow run = 10 QPS, peak -> 10 * 10 = 100 QPS\n        -> 600 workflow per min if each of them takes 1 minute (we need to take care of disk I/O, concurrency as well as reliablity) \n            as this is throughput intense. so it should be able to handle 600 workflows together atleast and during peak 60K Workflow together\n       \n- read heavy or write heavy: our system is write heavy we log every state transition \n    as well as have traces of what happened in each node of workflow but we still have clear relation between entities. \n \n> relational databases are not generally good for write heavy operations but to note our system is write heavy due to analytics, historic logs, traces of each node state transition, so we can use \npostgres for OLTP and clickhouse for OLAP.\n\n- we need to achieve eventual consistency, few millisecond delays in traces and logs are fine.  \n        ",
      "fontSize": 28.12226864818613,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "- Reliablity: we should be able to start our workflow from where it failed.\n\n- Scalablity: as we have assume 100k workflows from 1M runs atleast once. then we can say on avg atleast 10 workflow runs per day and nearly at any seconds nearly 10 are running. \n\n        -> 10 w/f running per day from 1M. \n        -> at any given second atleast 10 w/f are running. QPS for new workflow run = 10 QPS, peak -> 10 * 10 = 100 QPS\n        -> 600 workflow per min if each of them takes 1 minute (we need to take care of disk I/O, concurrency as well as reliablity) \n            as this is throughput intense. so it should be able to handle 600 workflows together atleast and during peak 60K Workflow together\n       \n- read heavy or write heavy: our system is write heavy we log every state transition \n    as well as have traces of what happened in each node of workflow but we still have clear relation between entities. \n \n> relational databases are not generally good for write heavy operations but to note our system is write heavy due to analytics, historic logs, traces of each node state transition, so we can use \npostgres for OLTP and clickhouse for OLAP.\n\n- we need to achieve eventual consistency, few millisecond delays in traces and logs are fine.  \n        ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
